  "path": "USAGE.md",
  "content": "# Digital Clock - Usage Guide\n\n## Getting Started\n\n### Installation\n\n1. Ensure Python 3.6+ is installed\n2. Install required package:\n   ```bash\n   pip install pytz\n   ```\n\n3. Run the application:\n   ```bash\n   python digital_clock.py\n   ```\n\n## Menu Navigation\n\n### Main Menu\n\nWhen you start the application, you'll see:\n\n```\n⏰ DIGITAL CLOCK - WORLD TIME ZONES ⏰\n\n1. Display simple format (Real-time updates)\n2. Display detailed format (Real-time updates)\n3. Display 7-segment format (Real-time updates)\n4. View all timezones\n5. Select timezones\n6. Exit\n```\n\n### Option 1: Simple Format\n\nShows a clean, easy-to-read table with:\n- Timezone code\n- Current time (HH:MM:SS)\n- Current date\n- UTC offset\n\n**Controls:**\n- Updates every second\n- Press `Ctrl+C` to return to main menu\n\n### Option 2: Detailed Format\n\nProvides comprehensive information:\n- Full timezone name\n- Current time with AM/PM\n- Complete date\n- UTC offset\n- Full timezone identifier\n\n**Controls:**\n- Updates every second\n- Press `Ctrl+C` to return to main menu\n\n### Option 3: 7-Segment Format\n\nRetro digital clock style:\n- Large digital display\n- Shows time as HH:MM:SS\n- One timezone per screen\n- Cycles through all selected timezones\n\n**Controls:**\n- Updates every second\n- Press `Ctrl+C` to return to main menu\n\n### Option 4: View All Timezones\n\nLists all 12 available timezones:\n- Timezone code\n- Full timezone name\n- Current time in that timezone\n\nPress Enter to return to main menu.\n\n### Option 5: Select Timezones\n\nCustomize which timezones are displayed:\n\n#### Sub-menu Options:\n\n**1. Add Timezone**\n- View all available timezones\n- Enter the timezone code you want to add\n- Timezone is added to your display list\n\n**2. Remove Timezone**\n- View currently selected timezones\n- Enter the number of the timezone to remove\n- Timezone is removed from your display list\n\n**3. Reset to Default**\n- Resets to: UTC, EST, PST, GMT, JST\n- Removes any custom selections\n\n**4. Back to Main Menu**\n- Returns to the main menu\n\n## Time Zone Codes\n\n| Code | Full Name | Region |\n|------|-----------|--------|\n| UTC  | Universal Time Coordinated | Global |\n| EST  | Eastern Standard Time | North America |\n| CST  | Central Standard Time | North America |\n| MST  | Mountain Standard Time | North America |\n| PST  | Pacific Standard Time | North America |\n| GMT  | Greenwich Mean Time | Europe/Africa |\n| CET  | Central European Time | Europe |\n| IST  | Indian Standard Time | Asia |\n| JST  | Japan Standard Time | Asia |\n| AEST | Australian Eastern Standard Time | Oceania |\n| NZST | New Zealand Standard Time | Oceania |\n| SGT  | Singapore Time | Asia |\n\n## Tips & Tricks\n\n### Organizing Your Display\n\n1. **For Global Business**: UTC, EST, GMT, JST, AEST\n2. **For Americas**: EST, CST, MST, PST\n3. **For Europe & Africa**: GMT, CET, IST\n4. **For Asia-Pacific**: JST, SGT, AEST, NZST\n\n### Keyboard Shortcuts\n\n- `Ctrl+C` - Exit any live display (returns to main menu)\n- No need to confirm timezone additions/removals - they're instant\n\n### Understanding UTC Offset\n\n- `UTC+HH:MM` - Hours and minutes ahead of UTC\n- `UTC-HH:MM` - Hours and minutes behind UTC\n- Example: `UTC+05:30` means 5 hours 30 minutes ahead of UTC (India)\n\n### Display Updates\n\nAll live displays update every second. The \"Last updated\" timestamp shows when the current display was refreshed.\n\n## Common Issues\n\n### No module named 'pytz'\n\n**Solution:**\n```bash\npip install pytz\n```\n\n### Display looks corrupted on Windows\n\n**Solution:**\n- Try running in Command Prompt instead of PowerShell\n- Or set UTF-8 encoding: `chcp 65001`\n\n### Time seems incorrect\n\n**Solution:**\n- Ensure your system time is correct\n- The application uses your system's time as reference\n\n## Examples\n\n### Example 1: Check Business Hours Across Timezones\n\n1. Open the application\n2. Select option 5 (Select Timezones)\n3. Add: EST, GMT, IST, JST\n4. Return to main menu\n5. Select option 1 (Simple format)\n6. You'll see all 4 business hub timezones\n\n### Example 2: Set Up a Meeting\n\n1. Select your timezones\n2. View in simple or detailed format\n3. Find a time that works for all zones\n4. Cross-reference with UTC offset if needed\n\n### Example 3: Track Server Time Across Data Centers\n\n1. Add timezones for all data center locations\n2. Use detailed format for full timezone names\n3. Monitor real-time updates\n\n## Performance Notes\n\n- Application runs smoothly on all systems\n- Updates every 1 second\n- Minimal CPU usage\n- Can run indefinitely\n\n## Exiting the Application\n\n- From main menu: Select option 6\n- From live displays: Press `Ctrl+C`\n- From selection menu: Select option 4\n"}\n]\n"}
